Data handling with Tidyverse

Today we will learn to:

  • Import and export data
  • Clean and reformat data
  • Filter data
  • Perform simple data mining on our datasets

The package that we are going to use is called tidyverse.

You can install it with:

install.packages('tidyverse')

What is tidyverse?

The tidyverse is a coherent system of packages for data manipulation, exploration and visualization that share a common design philosophy.

It contains several packages:

We will see a few commands from tibble and several from dplyr.

Tidy data

Tidy data is a standard way of mapping the meaning of a dataset to its structure.

In tidy data:

  • Every column is a variable.

  • Every row is an observation.

  • Every cell is a single value.

Having tidy data can avoid problems in the future.

You can tidy your data directly from R or from excel.

Lets import some data!

The most common format for data is tables. In R, table objects are called dataframes. Tidyverse has a specific type of dataframes, called tibbles. The most common command to import tibbles is read_tsv(). Remember, before starting to work, to activate the tidyverse package with the library(tidyverse) command.

data <- read_tsv('dogs.txt', show_col_types = FALSE)
head(data, n=5)
## # A tibble: 5 x 4
##   Name           Breed        Weight_kg OwnerCity          
##   <chr>          <chr>        <chr>     <chr>              
## 1 Spruzzolo      Sausage dog  na        Edo_Turin          
## 2 Nala           Mastiff      <NA>      Miguel_Barcelona   
## 3 Milou          Mastiff      138       Allison_Vancouver  
## 4 Mr Fluffypants Mastiff      110       Laura_Uppsala      
## 5 Colonel        Rough collie 50        Meredith_Birmingham

Using the pipe

The pipe is a fundamental tool which allows us to link commands. It is indicated by this characters: %>%

filter(data, Breed=='Mastiff') %>% arrange(Weight_kg) %>% head(n=2)
## # A tibble: 2 x 5
##   Name           Breed   Weight_kg Owner City   
##   <chr>          <chr>       <dbl> <chr> <chr>  
## 1 Gnasher        Mastiff        95 Amber London 
## 2 Mr Fluffypants Mastiff       110 Laura Uppsala

Using the pipe

The pipe is a fundamental tool which allows us to link commands. It is indicated by this characters: %>%

filter(data, Breed=='Mastiff') %>% arrange(Weight_kg) %>% head(n=2)
## # A tibble: 2 x 5
##   Name           Breed   Weight_kg Owner City   
##   <chr>          <chr>       <dbl> <chr> <chr>  
## 1 Gnasher        Mastiff        95 Amber London 
## 2 Mr Fluffypants Mastiff       110 Laura Uppsala
data %>% filter(Breed=='Mastiff') %>% arrange(Weight_kg) %>% head(n=2)
## # A tibble: 2 x 5
##   Name           Breed   Weight_kg Owner City   
##   <chr>          <chr>       <dbl> <chr> <chr>  
## 1 Gnasher        Mastiff        95 Amber London 
## 2 Mr Fluffypants Mastiff       110 Laura Uppsala

All the commands we saw can be linked with pipes.

The pull comamnd

The pipe is also useful to export tibble columns as normal R vectors. This can be useful if you want to do part of the analysis outside tidyverse.

data %>%  select(Weight_kg) %>% pull()
##  [1] 138 110  50  10  30  30  25  18  20  15  95  40

Filter supports boolean operators

The character | indicates OR. The character & indicates AND.

data %>% filter(Breed=='Lapponian herder' | Breed=='Dalmatian')
## # A tibble: 3 x 5
##   Name      Breed            Weight_kg Owner   City   
##   <chr>     <chr>                <dbl> <chr>   <chr>  
## 1 Pygmalian Dalmatian               25 Amber   London 
## 2 Irma      Lapponian herder        18 Matilda Uppsala
## 3 Pongo     Dalmatian               20 Cruella NewYork
data %>%  filter(Breed=='Mastiff' | Weight_kg > 100)
## # A tibble: 3 x 5
##   Name           Breed   Weight_kg Owner   City     
##   <chr>          <chr>       <dbl> <chr>   <chr>    
## 1 Milou          Mastiff       138 Allison Vancouver
## 2 Mr Fluffypants Mastiff       110 Laura   Uppsala  
## 3 Gnasher        Mastiff        95 Amber   London

Manipulate data

The command mutate is very flexible.

data  %>% mutate(Size=ifelse(Weight_kg > 20, 'Big', 'Small')) %>% head(n=5)
## # A tibble: 5 x 6
##   Name           Breed        Weight_kg Owner    City       Size 
##   <chr>          <chr>            <dbl> <chr>    <chr>      <chr>
## 1 Milou          Mastiff            138 Allison  Vancouver  Big  
## 2 Mr Fluffypants Mastiff            110 Laura    Uppsala    Big  
## 3 Colonel        Rough collie        50 Meredith Birmingham Big  
## 4 Aurelion       Sausage dog         10 Marcus   Stockholm  Small
## 5 Lassie         Rough collie        30 Svante   Uppsala    Big

Mutate can also use variable values

head(data, n=2)
## # A tibble: 2 x 5
##   Name           Breed   Weight_kg Owner   City     
##   <chr>          <chr>       <dbl> <chr>   <chr>    
## 1 Milou          Mastiff       138 Allison Vancouver
## 2 Mr Fluffypants Mastiff       110 Laura   Uppsala
data  %>% mutate(Owner=ifelse(Owner == 'Allison', 'Marcus',
                              data$Owner)) %>% head(n=2)
## # A tibble: 2 x 5
##   Name           Breed   Weight_kg Owner  City     
##   <chr>          <chr>       <dbl> <chr>  <chr>    
## 1 Milou          Mastiff       138 Marcus Vancouver
## 2 Mr Fluffypants Mastiff       110 Laura  Uppsala

Summarize data

The summarize command can be used to do basic analyses

data %>% summarize(MeanWeight=mean(Weight_kg))
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##   MeanWeight
##        <dbl>
## 1       48.4
data %>% summarize(MaxWeight=max(Weight_kg))
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##   MaxWeight
##       <dbl>
## 1       138

Other operations you can use are median, sd and min.

Summarize data with group_by

group_by can really enhance the usefullness of summarize

data %>% group_by(Breed) %>% summarize(MeanWeight=mean(Weight_kg))
## # A tibble: 6 x 2
##   Breed            MeanWeight
##   <chr>                 <dbl>
## 1 Dalmatian              22.5
## 2 Golden retriever       22.5
## 3 Lapponian herder       18  
## 4 Mastiff               114. 
## 5 Rough collie           40  
## 6 Sausage dog            10

Getting exact minimum and maximums

The command slice can get you the exact lines with the minimum or maximum of specific values

data %>% group_by(Breed) %>% slice(which.max(Weight_kg)
) %>% arrange(Weight_kg)

Fun exercises

Remember to add ‘https://raw.githubusercontent.com/mikdur/r-primer/main/lecture2/’ in front of the name of the datasets.

Load the datasets, remove lines with NAs and answer the following questions:

1: Which dog breeds have only 1 representative?

2: What is the combined weight of all dalmatians present in the dataset?

3: Who is the person owning most dogs?

4: Mastiffs cannot be that big, make it so that every mastiff weighting more than 90 kg has their weight set to 75 kg.

Actually

The AKC standard height (per their website) for this breed is 30 inches (76 cm) at the shoulder for males and 27.5 inches (70 cm) (minimum) at the shoulder for females. A typical male can weigh 150250 pounds (68113 kg), a typical female can weigh 120200 pounds (5491 kg), with very large individuals reaching 300 pounds (140 kg) or more. (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/English_Mastiff).

Fungi exercises

Import example_dataset.txt and do the following exercises:

1: Replace NAs in the Taxonomy column with “Fungi”.

2: Find out the median genome size in the dataset.

3: Find out which organism has the median genome size in the dataset.

4: Find out what is the average gene number in the Fusarium species?

FungiGenome exercises

Import F_graminearum.gff and do the following exercises:

1: How many genes are in the genome? On how many scaffolds are the genes located?

2: How many genes are on scaffold NC_026474.1?

3: Which scaffold has the most genes?

4: Add a column indicating the length of the genomic feature analysed on the line.

5: Which scaffold is the shortest?

Gff files explained

Every line shows informaton regarding a genomic feature, which can be a gene, an mRNA, a single exon or any othe unit that occupies space on the genome
